<h1>Jeddah Expat Guide 2026: Salaries, Red Sea Lifestyle, and Coastal Living</h1>

<p>Jeddah has always been the most cosmopolitan city in Saudi Arabia. Located on the Red Sea coast in the Hejaz region, it has served for centuries as the primary gateway for pilgrims traveling to Makkah and Madinah, giving it a diverse, multicultural character that sets it apart from any other Saudi city. With a population of approximately 4.7 million, Jeddah is the kingdom's second-largest city and its primary commercial port. Its residents include communities from across the Arab world, South and Southeast Asia, East Africa, and Europe, creating a cultural richness that is reflected in the city's food, architecture, and daily social rhythms. For expatriates in 2026, Jeddah offers a unique blend of coastal lifestyle, Red Sea outdoor recreation, competitive tax-free salaries, historical charm in the Al Balad heritage district, and proximity to transformative mega-projects including the Red Sea Global tourism development and KAUST, the King Abdullah University of Science and Technology.</p>

<p>Jeddah's proposition differs meaningfully from Riyadh. Where the capital offers concentration of Vision 2030 headquarters and the highest salary ceilings, Jeddah provides a more relaxed pace of life, direct access to world-class diving and marine recreation on the Red Sea, a gentler social environment rooted in centuries of cosmopolitan trade, and a cost of living that sits 10% to 15% below Riyadh in several key categories including housing and dining. The climate is distinct too: Jeddah's coastal humidity makes summers feel different from Riyadh's dry desert heat, and the winters are pleasantly mild. For professionals who value lifestyle balance alongside financial reward, particularly those in healthcare, tourism, hospitality, maritime, and education sectors, Jeddah consistently ranks among the most satisfying Gulf city assignments.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-8"><CostOfLivingSimulator client:visible defaultCity="jeddah" /></div>

<h2>Salaries in Jeddah</h2>
<p>The average expatriate salary in Jeddah is approximately SAR 10,000 to SAR 14,000 per month for mid-level professionals. Healthcare is one of the city's strongest sectors: King Faisal Specialist Hospital's Jeddah campus, Saudi German Hospital, Dr. Soliman Fakeeh Hospital, and other private institutions recruit international physicians at SAR 18,000 to SAR 45,000 depending on specialty and experience. International schools employ teachers at SAR 8,000 to SAR 16,000. Tourism and hospitality roles have expanded substantially due to the Red Sea tourism mega-project, which has created demand for hotel managers, marine tourism specialists, and hospitality professionals. KAUST, located approximately 80 kilometers north of Jeddah, offers internationally competitive academic and research salaries with a campus lifestyle that includes provided housing, recreation facilities, and a cosmopolitan community.</p>

<p>Port and logistics operations, centered on Jeddah Islamic Port, provide employment for supply chain managers, customs specialists, and maritime professionals at SAR 12,000 to SAR 25,000. The construction sector is active with infrastructure modernization, waterfront redevelopment, and the ongoing expansion of Jeddah's transportation network. Financial services, retail, and trading companies with regional operations offer mid-career salaries of SAR 10,000 to SAR 20,000. All figures represent entirely tax-free income for expatriates.</p>

<CostOfLivingBreakdown city="Jeddah" country="saudi-arabia" />

<h2>Cost of Living</h2>
<p>Jeddah's cost of living is slightly below Riyadh and substantially below Dubai. One-bedroom apartments in central areas like Al Hamra, Al Rawdah, or the Corniche district range from SAR 2,000 to SAR 4,500 per month. Two-bedroom apartments in established neighborhoods cost SAR 3,500 to SAR 7,000. Compound villas in expatriate-favored communities range from SAR 60,000 to SAR 160,000 annually. Budget apartments in areas further from the center, such as Al Hamdaniyah or Al Marwah, start from SAR 1,500.</p>

<p>Monthly groceries cost SAR 800 to SAR 1,600 at Danube, Bin Dawood, Tamimi, and LuLu. Jeddah's dining scene is particularly strong due to its multicultural population: Hejazi cuisine, Yemeni restaurants, Filipino food courts, Indian and Pakistani dining, and international restaurants cover every budget from SAR 12 for street food to SAR 100 or more at mid-range waterfront restaurants. <a href="/saudi-arabia/utilities/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">Utilities</a> through SEC cost SAR 250 to SAR 600 monthly, with air conditioning demand peaking during the humid summer months. Petrol at SAR 2.18 per liter keeps transportation costs low. A single professional can live comfortably on SAR 4,500 to SAR 7,500 per month, while families should budget SAR 10,000 to SAR 20,000 depending on school fees and housing choices.</p>

<h2>Neighborhoods</h2>
<p>The Corniche area along the Red Sea waterfront is Jeddah's most desirable residential strip, offering proximity to the famous Jeddah Corniche, King Fahd Fountain, and an array of restaurants and cafes. Apartments here range from SAR 3,000 to SAR 6,000 for one-bedrooms. Al Hamra, south of the Corniche, is a well-established expatriate neighborhood with compound villas, parks, and easy access to the American and British consulates. Rent for compound living in Al Hamra runs SAR 70,000 to SAR 140,000 annually.</p>

<p>Al Rawdah and Al Zahra in the northern part of the city offer modern apartments and proximity to malls and international schools at SAR 2,500 to SAR 5,000 for one-bedrooms. Obhur, further north, is popular with families seeking beach access and a suburban feel, though commute times to central Jeddah can exceed 30 minutes during peak traffic. Al Balad, the historic old town and UNESCO World Heritage Site, offers a fascinating living environment for culturally curious expatriates willing to trade modern conveniences for architectural character and deep historical atmosphere. For budget options, areas south and east of central Jeddah provide apartments starting from SAR 1,200 to SAR 2,000.</p>

<h2>Red Sea Lifestyle and Outdoor Activities</h2>
<p>Jeddah's Red Sea coastline is the city's defining lifestyle advantage. The Red Sea is home to some of the world's most spectacular coral reef systems, supporting a vibrant diving and snorkeling community. Dive clubs including Red Sea Divers, Jeddah Dive Club, and Desert Sea Divers offer PADI certification courses, guided dives, and boat trips to offshore reef sites. The underwater visibility, variety of marine life (including manta rays, whale sharks, and hundreds of tropical fish species), and warm water temperatures make Red Sea diving a year-round activity. A typical weekend dive trip costs SAR 300 to SAR 600 per person including equipment rental and boat transport.</p>

<p>The Jeddah Corniche stretches 30 kilometers along the waterfront, providing a landscaped promenade with parks, sculptures, playgrounds, restaurants, and the iconic King Fahd Fountain, which shoots water over 300 meters into the air. Evening walks along the Corniche are a daily ritual for Jeddah residents. Private beach resorts along the Obhur coast offer swimming, jet skiing, sailing, and beachfront dining. Camping on the coast north and south of the city is popular during the cooler months. The proximity to the Hejaz mountains provides hiking opportunities in areas like Al Shafa and Taif, both reachable within a two-hour drive. Weekend trips to Taif, the summer capital at 1,800 meters elevation, offer relief from coastal humidity and access to rose farms, historic souqs, and mountain views.</p>

<h2>Al Balad: UNESCO Heritage District</h2>
<p>Al Balad, Jeddah's historic old town, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site that preserves the traditional coral-stone architecture of the Hejazi merchant class. The district's narrow lanes, decorated wooden mashrabiyya balconies, and centuries-old mosques offer a living connection to the city's past as a crossroads of Red Sea trade and pilgrimage. A major restoration program has revitalized sections of Al Balad with art galleries, boutique cafes, traditional craft shops, and cultural spaces. Walking tours through the district reveal historical significance at every turn: Bab Makkah gate, Nassif House (a restored 19th-century merchant palace), and the oldest sections of the Jeddah Souq. For expatriates interested in history and culture, Al Balad provides a depth of heritage that no other Saudi city can match.</p>

<h2>Working in Jeddah</h2>
<p>Jeddah's economy is anchored by trade (Jeddah Islamic Port handles approximately 60% of Saudi Arabia's non-oil imports), healthcare, construction, and increasingly, tourism and entertainment. The Chamber of Commerce district in Al Rawdah hosts regional offices for multinational companies. The banking sector is represented by branches of all major Saudi banks. The construction sector is active with waterfront redevelopment, infrastructure modernization, and projects linked to the broader Vision 2030 agenda. KAUST, located north of Jeddah near Thuwal, operates as a self-contained research university community with internationally recruited faculty and staff. Working hours follow the Sunday-to-Thursday schedule, with prayer break accommodations.</p>

<h2>Education</h2>
<p>Jeddah's <a href="/saudi-arabia/education/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">international school</a> options include the British International School of Jeddah (BISJ), the American International School of Jeddah, Continental School, and Jeddah Knowledge International School. Fees range from SAR 25,000 to SAR 70,000 annually for British and American curricula. Indian schools including the International Indian School Jeddah and Al Falah International School charge SAR 8,000 to SAR 18,000. The school landscape is somewhat smaller than Riyadh's but covers all major curricula. KAUST's campus school serves families living on the university campus with a curriculum aligned to international standards.</p>

<h2>Healthcare</h2>
<p>King Faisal Specialist Hospital's Jeddah campus provides tertiary care, while private hospitals including Dr. Soliman Fakeeh Hospital, Saudi German Hospital Jeddah, and International Medical Center offer comprehensive services. <a href="/saudi-arabia/healthcare/" class="text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-400 hover:underline">CCHI insurance</a> is mandatory for all expatriates. The healthcare sector is a major employer, actively recruiting international physicians, nurses, and allied health professionals. Pharmacies are abundant, and most Western medications are readily available. Emergency services are accessible at 997 for ambulance.</p>

<h2>Climate Considerations</h2>
<p>Jeddah's climate differs significantly from Riyadh. Summer temperatures reach 40 to 43 degrees Celsius with humidity often exceeding 70%, creating an oppressive combination from June through September. The high humidity means that even shade provides limited relief, and air conditioning is essential in homes, cars, and all commercial spaces. Winter months from November through March are Jeddah's best season, with pleasant temperatures of 18 to 28 degrees and lower humidity. Spring and autumn offer warm but manageable conditions. The coastal location means Jeddah rarely experiences sandstorms but does occasionally see heavy rainfall during winter months, which can cause flash flooding in some low-lying areas due to limited drainage infrastructure.</p>

